  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Pediatric cardiac arrest is an uncommon but critical life-threatening event requiring
      effective cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR). About 16,000 pediatric cardiac arrests occurs
      in the United States annually. Only 8% of the patients survive to hospital discharge and of
      these, up to two-thirds have neurological sequelae. Majority of pediatric cardiac arrest are
      below age of two and have poorer chance of survival versus older children
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
